I don&#39;t understand anything about your attempt; to start, string objects like `posts` don&#39;t have a `stream()` method, and the rest just seems like a bunch of random stuff with no rhyme or reason... I think you&#39;re really confused about some things and/or making it more complicated than it needs to be, so here&#39;s a small simple example that extracts hashtags from a string in sorted order, with comments describing each step:

```java
import java.util.regex.*;
import java.util.List;

public class Foo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String posts = &quot;Example #java #streams string etc.&quot;;

        // Define a hashtag as a # followed by one or more alphanumeric
        // characters and a word boundary.
        Pattern hashtag_re = Pattern.compile(&quot;#[a-zA-Z0-9]+\\b&quot;);

        List&lt;String&gt; hashtags =
            hashtag_re.matcher(posts).results() // Stream of MatchResult objects
            .map(MatchResult::group) // Extract the matched text from each;
                                     // now a stream of Strings
            .sorted() // Sort the tags
            .distinct() // Remove duplicates
            .toList(); // Convert to a list (Old versions of java might need
                       // .collect(Collectors.toList()) instead)

        System.out.println(&quot;There are &quot;
                           + hashtags.size()
                           + &quot; hashtags: &quot;
                           + hashtags);
    }

}
```

